      Elsewhere in US bank rescues
   =20
 =20

Things seem   less urgent at First Republic?

Wall Street leaders and US officials discussing an intervention at First Re=
public Bank are exploring the possibility of government backing to encourag=
e a deal that would shore up the lender, people with knowledge of the situa=
tion said. The shares dropped Wednesday morning.
The group has floated a variety of measures to make the company more attrac=
tive to potential investors or a buyer, part of an effort to ensure there i=
sn=E2=80=99t another US bank failure, the people said, asking not to be nam=
ed describing confidential talks.=C2=A0
Among options, the government could play a role in lifting assets out of Fi=
rst Republic that have eroded its balance sheet. While investors have expre=
ssed interest in helping, the firm=E2=80=99s unrealized losses have been a =
sticking point. Additional ideas have included offering liability protectio=
n, applying capital rules more flexibly or easing limits on ownership stake=
s, the people said.
The talks are continuing. A variety of issues remain unresolved and an agre=
ement isn=E2=80=99t guaranteed, the people said. It=E2=80=99s unclear how t=
he government would provide any financial support.

Imagine putting dollar numbers on the investors=E2=80=99 demands. Imagine s=
ome bigger bank saying =E2=80=9Cokay we=E2=80=99ll buy First Republic but w=
e want $5 billion of goodies from the government in exchange.=E2=80=9D Good=
ies might include:
=09The government buying or guaranteeing some of the worse assets.=09The go=
vernment indemnifying the buyer against some liabilities.=09=E2=80=9CApplyi=
ng capital rules more flexibly.=E2=80=9D=09=E2=80=9CEasing limits on owners=
hip stakes.=E2=80=9D

And the bank has some schedule of how it values each goodie and is indiffer=
ent to any package that totals $5 billion worth of goodies. It is I guess f=
airly straightforward to reduce Options 1 and 2 to dollars, and also pretty=
 symmetric: A $5 billion loss-sharing deal is worth about $5 billion to the=
 buyer and costs the government about $5 billion.
  [2]
 I bet that a bank could put a price on=C2=A0Option 3; that is, it could pr=
obably calculate how much more profitable it would be with lower capital re=
quirements. Could the government put a price on it? Is that price symmetric=
? Does saying =E2=80=9Csure, big bank, be undercapitalized for a while=E2=
=80=9D cost the government as much as it benefits the buyer bank? More? Les=
s? Has the value of financial stability (and thus bank capital) gone up due=
 to this crisis, or is taking a bit of risk with capital requirements a che=
ap way out of it?
Meanwhile   at Signature Bank:

Signature Bank=E2=80=99s partial takeover by a competitor is notable for wh=
at it doesn=E2=80=99t include: $11 billion of loans against a class of New =
York City apartments whose values have tumbled in recent years.
In a deal with the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., New York Community Banc=
orp Inc. is buying more than $34 billion in Signature=E2=80=99s deposits, a=
s well as $13 billion in loans and 40 bank branches. Left behind is the com=
mercial real estate debt portfolio, weighted heavily toward multifamily bui=
ldings bound by a law that restricts landlords=E2=80=99 ability to raise re=
nts.
=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s toxic waste,=E2=80=9D said Christopher Whalen, chairm=
an of Whalen Global Advisors. =E2=80=9CFrom an investor point of view, thes=
e are dead assets.=E2=80=9D

The   basic story of this month=E2=80=99s US bank runs seems to be that int=
erest rates went up and the value of regional banks=E2=80=99 portfolios of =
safe held-to-maturity bonds went down. These values were not reflected in t=
he banks=E2=80=99 financial statements (because accounting rules allow them=
 to mark held-to-maturity bonds at their purchase price), but they were ref=
lected in the footnotes to those statements, and eventually analysts and de=
positors read those footnotes and got nervous and took their money out. And=
 so SVB and Signature failed and were seized by the FDIC.
But meanwhile those banks also have loans, and the loans (1) might have som=
e credit problems and (2) probably also have some interest-rate problems, s=
ince they were mostly made in much lower-interest-rate environments. But th=
e loans are harder to value and harder to sell; there is not some table at =
the back of the financial statements listing the exact market value of the =
loan portfolio. The loans probably did not bring down the banks. But now th=
at the FDIC owns these banks, it can sell the bond portfolios easily enough=
: They=E2=80=99re just bonds. It turns out that no one wants some of the lo=
ans, though, so the FDIC is stuck with them.
And   at PacWest:

PacWest Bancorp is moving to shore up liquidity to protect itself after cus=
tomers pulled 20% of their deposits since the start of the year.
The regional bank, whose shares have tumbled 58% this month, obtained $1.4 =
billion from a financing facility from Apollo Global Management-owned inves=
tment firm Atlas SP Partners and abandoned a separate push to raise capital=
 because of market volatility, it said in a statement Wednesday.

It used to be that banks funded themselves with deposits and used the money=
 to make loans to private equity firms. Now banks fund themselves with loan=
s from private equity firms.

