   =20
      AT1s
   =20
 =20

A general dynamic in bank rescues is:
=09You want the shareholders of the failed bank to take big losses, because=
 (1) the whole point of equity capital at a bank is to bear losses before d=
epositors or taxpayers and (2) you want to punish the shareholders to=C2=A0=
discourage=C2=A0other=C2=A0banks from taking dumb risks.=09To avoid contagi=
on, you want all the=C2=A0other=C2=A0banks to shore up their balance sheets=
 by selling stock to raise loss-absorbing equity capital.

There is a tension here. If you seize the riskiest bank and give its shareh=
olders nothing, to make an example of them, then the second-riskiest bank i=
s going to have a hard time raising equity, which means it is more likely t=
o fail and need rescuing itself. If you bail out the riskiest bank in a way=
 that preserves a lot of value for shareholders, then (1) the second-riskie=
st bank is going to be a bit more sanguine about its own risks and (2) the =
equity didn=E2=80=99t do much good, did it?
Similarly with additional tier 1 capital securities. We have   talked over =
the last few days   about how Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=99s AT1 bonds we=
re wiped out in its forced merger with UBS Group AG over the weekend, even =
as Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s shareholders got about $3 billion of value in th=
e deal. AT1 holders, at Credit Suisse and elsewhere, are outraged that they=
 did worse than shareholders, and non-Swiss banking regulators have rushed =
to assure the market that=C2=A0they=C2=A0would never treat AT1s that way. I=
 have argued that it was fine and good to zero the AT1s even while paying t=
he shareholders a bit, but never mind that.
The main point here is that, whether or not the common stock got anything, =
whether or not the AT1 triggers were met as a strict legal matter, this is =
a rescue in which Swiss authorities are providing asset guarantees and liqu=
idity backstops and other aid to UBS: a bailout, of sorts, at taxpayer expe=
nse, or taxpayer risk anyway. And Credit Suisse had 16 billion Swiss francs=
 of AT1 securities that were intended precisely to avoid that, to bear loss=
es before taxpayers do, to go to zero if a bailout looks=C2=A0necessary. An=
d so the Swiss authorities zeroed the AT1s. If you=E2=80=99re not going to =
zero the AT1s while doing a government-backstopped rescue of a giant global=
 bank over a weekend, what is the point of the AT1s? If they don=E2=80=99t =
bear losses here, why bother issuing them, and why treat them as loss-absor=
bing capital?
  [3]

On the other hand it is good for banks to issue AT1s, to bear losses in ris=
ky times, and  now they kind of can=E2=80=99t:

The wipeout of $17bn of Credit Suisse bonds has thrown into question furthe=
r issuance in the market for risky bank debt, with some of Asia=E2=80=99s b=
iggest banks considering pausing sales.
Major banks in Japan, Singapore and Hong Kong are placing new additional ti=
er 1 (AT1) bond deals on hold until market conditions stabilise, according =
to people familiar with the plans.
The hiatus follows three days of turmoil triggered by the decision to write=
 down the value of Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1 bond to zero as part of the =
bank=E2=80=99s takeover by Swiss rival UBS, while shareholders received $3.=
25bn. AT1s are a class of debt designed to take losses when institutions ru=
n into trouble but are generally believed to rank ahead of equity on the ba=
lance sheet.
Regulators in the eurozone, UK and Hong Kong have stressed that they will n=
ot follow Swiss authorities in upsetting the usual hierarchy of bank credit=
ors.
Even so, prices in the $260bn AT1 market have tumbled this week. Analysts a=
nd investors have warned that buyers are likely to demand substantially hig=
her borrowing costs, potentially creating a =E2=80=9Czombie market=E2=80=9D=
 where banks are reluctant to issue fresh debt to refinance older bonds. =
=E2=80=A6
The fallout from the Credit Suisse deal =E2=80=9Cchanges the whole nature o=
f the [AT1] market, and I think the ability to issue going forward is proba=
bly close to zero=E2=80=9D, said Greg Peters, co-chief investment officer o=
f PGIM Fixed Income. =E2=80=9CBasically, it=E2=80=99s a zombie market going=
 forward in my mind.=E2=80=9D

In general when a bond investor says =E2=80=9Cno one will ever buy these bo=
nds again,=E2=80=9D you should check back in after lunchtime and he=E2=80=
=99ll probably be buying them; Argentina infamously  issued a 100-year bond=
=C2=A0three=C2=A0years after its   previous debt default and three years be=
fore its  next one. Still, sure, it would be nice if global banks could iss=
ue more capital securities now,=C2=A0but the Credit Suisse treatment has ch=
illed that market.=C2=A0
Elsewhere in the=C2=A0Asian AT1 market:

Asian private bank clients led selling on Monday, where some panicked selle=
rs pushed down AT1s issued by banks in Asia by between 2 and 10 points, dep=
ending on the country. The market for the bonds recovered on Tuesday but As=
ia AT1s were still lower than last week.
The selling included wealthy clients who owned the AT1s with leverage and w=
ere receiving margin calls, said two private bankers.
Retail investors in Europe do not typically hold AT1s, and they are barred =
from doing so in jurisdictions including the UK.
In Asia, the instruments were popular with wealthy individuals who apprecia=
ted the brand names and the yields. A Credit Suisse bond issued last year a=
nd paying a 9.75 per cent coupon was particularly popular.

One well-known feature of bank rescues is that the=C2=A0legal terms=C2=A0of=
 a bank=E2=80=99s funding often matter less than=C2=A0who holds them=C2=A0a=
nd how interconnected they are. Silicon Valley Bank failed with tens of bil=
lions of dollars of uninsured deposits, which, as you can tell by the name,=
 were=C2=A0not=C2=A0insured by the government. The government insured=C2=A0=
them anyway, because SVB=E2=80=99s uninsured depositors were in various way=
s politically powerful, or sympathetic, or economically important; freezing=
 the money that a bunch of startups needed to make payroll would be=C2=A0ba=
d for the economy.=C2=A0
Similarly it would be bad if AT1 securities were mostly held in small retai=
l accounts by retirees who relied on them for income: If zeroing AT1s would=
 impose serious hardship on ordinary people, then that is hard for a regula=
tor to do, which means that the AT1s can=E2=80=99t fulfill their purpose of=
 absorbing=C2=A0losses. So banning them from retail accounts seems like goo=
d bank regulation. On the other hand, if Swiss bank AT1s are=C2=A0not=C2=A0=
held by Swiss retirees, but=C2=A0are=C2=A0held by wealthy Asian individuals=
,=C2=A0then that is in some ways politically ideal: The Swiss regulators ge=
t to impose losses on people who (1) can afford them and (2) don=E2=80=99t =
vote in Switzerland. (Though, if=C2=A0the combined UBS/Credit Suisse=E2=80=
=99s   wealth management business in Asia=C2=A0is an important part of its =
success, imposing losses on those clients has some problems.)
By the way, it=E2=80=99s also bad if AT1s are held in margin accounts at ba=
nks! You don=E2=80=99t want banks to have much exposure to other banks=E2=
=80=99 AT1s, because then zeroing one bank=E2=80=99s AT1 causes losses at o=
ther banks and can create contagion.

