<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SVB</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Silicon Valley Bank was shut down by the Feder=
al Deposit Insurance Corp. on Friday, March 10, for running out of money. I=
t is of course bad for a bank to run out of money. But it is also a little =
hard to understand how a bank like SVB could have run out of money, in the =
US, in 2023. The structure of the modern banking system is supposed to prev=
ent that, and SVB seemed in some ways like a bank that was particularly unl=
ikely to run out of money. But it did.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The very stylized <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0d=
XAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDMyMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1=
dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMzIyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN=
0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB75db6fbe" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  facts of SVB</a> are t=
hat it had about $190 billion of deposits and invested much of that money =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0call it $120 billion =E2=80=94=C2=A0in=C2=A0a portfolio of m=
ostly=C2=A0Treasury and agency bonds. The rest was invested in more complic=
ated, riskier, traditional banking assets (loans, etc.), but SVB actually d=
id <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30923484.257437=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucGhpbGFkZWxwaGlhZmVkLm9yZy90aGUtZWNvbm9teS9iYW5raW5nLWFuZC=
1maW5hbmNpYWwtbWFya2V0cy9iYW5raW5nLXRyZW5kcy10aGUtcmlzZS1pbi1sb2FuLXRvLWRlc=
G9zaXQtcmF0aW9zLWlzLTgwLXRoZS1uZXctNjA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa479adfa" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> relatively=C2=A0<em>little=C2=A0</em>lending</a>, for a bank, and h=
ad rather a lot of safe bonds.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course those bonds=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNvdWxkbi10LWlnbm9y=
ZS1pdHMtbG9zc2VzLWJ1dC10aGUtZmVkLWNhbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjImdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmYjeGo0eTd2emtn/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB111d010=
9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">turned out to be risky</a>, too, since interest rates went up,=
 the market value of the bonds declined, the bank became insolvent on a mar=
k-to-market basis, depositors noticed, and there was a run on the bank. Abo=
ut=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30923484.2=
57437/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZnBpLmNhLmdvdi93cC1jb250ZW50L3VwbG9hZHMvc2l0ZXMvMzM3LzIwM=
jMvMDMvREZQSS1PcmRlcnMtU2lsaWNvbi1WYWxsZXktQmFuay0wMzEwMjAyMy5wZGY_ZW1yYz1i=
ZWRjMDk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd147b2c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">$42 billion of deposits =
fled</a> on SVB=E2=80=99s worst day, Thursday, March 9, leaving the bank wi=
th =E2=80=9Ca negative cash balance of approximately $958 million=E2=80=9D;=
 it closed the next day. Fine. But=C2=A0SVB had invested about=C2=A0$120 bi=
llion in=C2=A0high-quality liquid bonds, and even after rates went up and t=
he bonds lost value, they=C2=A0were probably still worth about $100 billion=
. But=C2=A0losing $42 billion of deposits broke the bank.=C2=A0These number=
s are imprecise, they don=E2=80=99t account for outflows prior to that Thur=
sday, etc., but still, 100 is a lot more than 42. If you have $100 billion =
of Treasuries, you can probably use them to acquire much more than $42 bill=
ion of cash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can sell them, for instance, though that m=
ight take a while. But more to the point you can=C2=A0<em>borrow against th=
em</em>; you can post them as collateral to a lender to get cash. In partic=
ular, in modern banking systems, a bank can post Treasuries as collateral t=
o borrow money from=C2=A0its lender of last resort, the central bank (in th=
e US, the Federal Reserve); the Fed can just <em>create=C2=A0</em>money, so=
 lending billions of dollars against good collateral is no sweat for it.=C2=
=A0In the US, there is also a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvZmVkZXJhbC1ob21lLWxvYW4tYmFua3MtdG8tcmFpc2UtN=
jQtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi1ub3Rlcy1vZmZlcmluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMzIyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1=
dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAzMjImdXR=
tX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBedc8bcd4" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">len=
der of next-to-last resort</a>,=E2=80=9D the Federal Home Loan Bank system,=
 which will also lend cash to banks with Treasuries as collateral. If Silic=
on Valley Bank had had $190 billion of deposits and $190 billion of weird b=
espoke risky small-business loans, it might have had a hard time borrowing =
$42 billion against those loans to pay out fleeing depositors. But it had $=
100 billion-ish of simple high-quality Treasury and agency bonds, so it=E2=
=80=99s a little weird that it couldn=E2=80=99t find $42 billion.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These numbers are all approximate and hand-wav=
e-y, and you could imagine a reasonable explanation like =E2=80=9Csure it l=
ost $42 billion of deposits that day, but it lost billions in the previous =
days too, and even if it had been able to borrow the $42 billion it would h=
ave lost billions more the next day, so the Fed and FHLB pulled the plug wh=
en they saw it was hopeless.=E2=80=9D And I have vaguely assumed that was t=
he explanation for why SVB couldn=E2=80=99t get the money to pay out its de=
positors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But today at the Wall Street Journal=C2=A0Hann=
ah Miao, Gregory Zuckerman and Ben Eisen <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/30923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xl=
cy9ob3ctdGhlLWxhc3QtZGl0Y2gtZWZmb3J0LXRvLXNhdmUtc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktYmFuay1=
mYWlsZWQtODk2MTljYjI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB50cb0a87" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> have the=
=C2=A0<em>actual</em>, horrifying<em>=C2=A0</em>explanation</a>, which is t=
hat the Fed=E2=80=99s computers go to bed at 4 p.m. and you can=E2=80=99t w=
ake them up until the next morning:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Withdrawals accelerated late in the morning on=
 the West Coast on Thursday, March 9. Executives paced the office on phone =
calls as employees watched and texted details to each other. =C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is when SVB, at the time controlled by SV=
B Financial Group, started looking for help, only to run into the U.S.=E2=
=80=99s bank-funding system, which wasn=E2=80=99t built for speed. First it=
 turned to the San Francisco Federal Home Loan Bank, asking for a $20 billi=
on loan. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was already midday in California, and SVB=
=E2=80=99s unusually large request came too late for the San Francisco FHLB=
 to process that day, people familiar with the matter said. It offered SVB =
a smaller loan but the bank turned that down, the people said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB turned to plan B, asking the San Francisco=
 FHLB to move $20 billion of collateral to the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s di=
scount window, where it could get emergency funding, the people said. SVB h=
ad roughly $20 billion available for financing at the San Francisco FHLB, a=
ccording to the people familiar with the matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank hit another roadblock. The transfer r=
equired procedural steps. SVB had outstanding loans at the San Francisco FH=
LB, which had to determine how much collateral it needed to hold, the peopl=
e familiar with the matter said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB also tried to get $20 billion in assets to=
 the Fed through Bank of New York Mellon Corp., one of its custodial banks.=
 SVB was too late=E2=80=94it had missed BNY Mellon=E2=80=99s daily cutoff f=
or instructions for Fed transfers from custodial accounts.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BNY tried to extend its cutoff, but:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Fed needed a test trade to be =
run before the actual transfer could occur. That took time and the Fed didn=
=E2=80=99t extend its own daily deadline of 4 p.m. PT for collateral transf=
ers to help SVB. Time ran out on the bankers and SVB couldn=E2=80=99t get t=
he money that day.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It did get the money the next day, but by that=
 point the FDIC had already seized it. Now, again, even if it=C2=A0<em>had=
=C2=A0</em>gotten the cash, it was facing continuing deposit flight, it see=
ms to have been economically insolvent and it probably would not have survi=
ved the weekend. The Journal notes:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some people at SVB remain angry ab=
out the takeover and frustrated that a possible rescue took so long. They s=
ay the bank was seized just before it got a lifeline from the Fed or a buye=
r, but they also acknowledge that the scale of withdrawals doomed the bank.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do not actually think that the banking crisi=
s of the last two weeks =E2=80=94 in which SVB and Signature Bank of New Yo=
rk have failed, other US regional banks have teetered, the Fed and FDIC hav=
e provided extraordinary support to the banking system, Credit Suisse Group=
 AG disappeared over the weekend, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0all could have been a=
voided if the Fed had said =E2=80=9Chmm, normally we do a test transaction =
first, but you seem to be in a rush and it=E2=80=99s getting toward closing=
 time so we=E2=80=99ll just skip that and go straight to lending you the mo=
ney.=E2=80=9D SVB=E2=80=99s problems were bigger than the Fed=E2=80=99s 4 p=
.m. transfer cutoff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yet! Man! What the heck! A <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc=
GJzLm9yZy9uZXdzaG91ci9lY29ub215L2JhbmstcnVucy11c2VkLXRvLWJlLXNsb3ctdGhlLWRp=
Z2l0YWwtZXJhLWhhcy1zcGVkLXRoaW5ncy11cA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4edbcdc5" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> lot</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30=
923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZ3VhcmRpYW4uY29tL2J1c2luZXNzLzIwMjMvbWFyL=
zE2L3RoZS1maXJzdC10d2l0dGVyLWZ1ZWxsZWQtYmFuay1ydW4taG93LXNvY2lhbC1tZWRpYS1j=
b21wb3VuZGVkLXN2YnMtY29sbGFwc2U/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf7bd4da4" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 has</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30923484.=
257437/aHR0cHM6Ly9mb3J0dW5lLmNvbS8yMDIzLzAzLzE0L2ZpbmFuY2lhbC1yZWd1bGF0b3Jz=
LXVucHJlcGFyZWQtYmFuay1ydW5zLWFnZS1zb2NpYWwtbWVkaWEtc2lsaWNvbi12YWxsZXktYmF=
uay1zdmItdGVjaC12Yy1icmFkbGV5LXR1c2sv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB92257ca6" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> been</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30=
923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmFuZC5vcmcvYmxvZy8yMDIzLzAzL2ZpbmFuY2lhbC1wY=
W5pYy1pbi10aGUtYWdlLW9mLWRpZ2l0YWwtYmFua2luZy1zb2NpYWwuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBa1408643" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> written</a> about how SVB was a bank run for=
 a speedier, modern age. Instead of hearing a rumor at the coffee shop and =
running down to the bank branch to wait on line to withdraw your money, now=
 you can hear a rumor on Twitter or the group chat and use an app=C2=A0to w=
ithdraw money instantly. A tech-friendly bank with a highly digitally conne=
cted set of depositors can lose 25% of its deposits in hours, which did not=
 seem conceivable in previous eras of bank runs.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the other part of the problem is that, whi=
le depositors can panic faster and banks can give them their money faster, =
the lender-of-last-resort system on which all of this relies is still stuck=
 in a slower, more leisurely era.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CWhen the user interface imp=
roves faster than the core system, it means customers can act faster than t=
he bank can react,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/30923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlZGlmZi5jby9hcmNoaXZlL2xvbmdyZ=
WFkcy1vcGVuLXRocmVhZC0xNi8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBba8bb737" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrot=
e Byrne Hobart</a>. You can panic in an instant and withdraw your money wit=
h an app, but the bank can=E2=80=99t get more money without a series of pho=
ne calls and test trades that can only happen during regular business hours=
. And so sometimes a bank that theoretically has a lot of liquidity can jus=
t run out of cash.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There will be all sorts of proposals for chang=
es in bank regulation and supervision and deposit insurance and Fed facilit=
ies that come out of this crisis. =E2=80=9CMake the=C2=A0lender-of-last-res=
ort process for making loans and=C2=A0posting collateral a=C2=A0bit more au=
tomated=E2=80=9D is probably not going to be top of the list: Again, I doub=
t it would have=C2=A0<em>saved=C2=A0</em>SVB, and I do not have any great t=
echnical insights into=C2=A0<em>how=C2=A0</em>it should be improved.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But, I don=E2=80=99t know, wouldn=E2=80=99t it be a good idea? Wo=
uldn=E2=80=99t you have more confidence in the banking system, if banks tha=
t had lots of assets could get money when they needed it?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/30923484.257437/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjEvc3ZiLWZpbmFuY2lhbC13aWxsLW5lZWQtdG8td2FpdC=
10by1nZXQtYmFjay0yLWJpbGxpb24tZnJvbS1mZGljP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAzMjIyM19NT05FWVNUV=
UZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDMy=
MiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB07bfe564" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  SVB deposit flight</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The former owner of Silicon Valley Bank, seize=
d earlier this month by regulators, will need to wait, possibly for several=
 months, to know if it can get back about $2 billion in cash it would need =
to repay bondholders and other creditors.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB Financial Group won provisional court appr=
oval Tuesday to spend only a fraction of the cash the company claims federa=
l regulators must return. What happens with the rest of the money will need=
 to be decided in the coming months, with lawyers for bondholders owed more=
 than $3.3 billion saying they are concerned that the Federal Deposit Insur=
ance Corp. will try to keep the cash.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB Financial, the holding company, has variou=
s assets that are not part of the bank that the FDIC seized, and that can b=
e used to pay its creditors in bankruptcy. But one of those assets is $2 bi=
llion in accounts=C2=A0<em>at SVB (the bank)</em>, and the FDIC controls th=
e bank, and it doesn=E2=80=99t want to give the deposits back. Presumably t=
his is because (1) the FDIC thinks the bank might have some claims against =
the holding company, (2) it is always better to litigate those claims=C2=A0=
<em>while you are holding the money</em>, and (3) there is a general philos=
ophical distastefulness about holding-company creditors getting paid while =
the bank is insolvent, there is not enough money to pay depositors, and the=
 FDIC has to make up the difference. =E2=80=9CWhen a bank fails and can=E2=
=80=99t pay depositors, its holding-company bondholders get nothing=E2=80=
=9D is not quite the law, but you can see why it might be the FDIC=E2=80=99=
s policy preference, and right now they=E2=80=99ve got the cash.</p>
